GE's stock falls as Jeff Immelt's 64th and last quarter is another disappointment
BY MarketWatch— 10:03 AM ET 07/22/2017


  Shares suffered the worst one-day post-earnings performance in over four years
  Shares of General Electric Co. (GE) tumbled to the lowest close in nearly two years on Friday, as outgoing Chief Executive
Jeff Immelt ended his reign of the industrial conglomerate with a downbeat outlook.
  But Friday's share weakness may come as little surprise to long-term investors. The company (GE) has lost about $170
billion in market value while Immelt has been in charge, according to FactSet data, which is more than the value of 14
of the current components of the Dow Jones Industrial Average. .
  Friday's selloff marked the eighth-straight quarter the shares declined on the day results were reported. The 2.9%
drop was the biggest one-day post-results decline since it fell 4.1% on April 19, 2013.
  The stock had initially rallied after GE's second-quarter report was released (http://www.marketwatch.com/story/ges-
stock-gains-after-profit-and-sales-beat-expectations-2017-07-21), to be up as much as 1.8% at about 6:45 a.m. ET, as the
company handily beat profit and sales expectations. The stock trended lower leading up to the post-results conference
call (http://www.marketwatch.com/story/ges-stock-turns-sharply-lower-after-ceo-immelt-gives-downbeat-outlook-on-
conference-call-2017-07-21), with the stock down 0.9% just before the call started.
  See also: GE cuts costs buy shares hit by weak outlook (http://www.marketwatch.com/story/ge-cuts-costs-but-shares-hit-
by-weak-outlook-2017-07-21).
  Immelt said the recovery for the oil and gas market has been "slower and more volatile" than what was planned, and has
customers have been delaying purchases, he expects results for the legacy oil and gas business to be "lower than
previously anticipated," according to a transcript of the call provided by FactSet.
  For the power business, GE's largest by revenue, Immelt said the company was planning for a "down market" this year
and for 2018.
  "Given our outlook on oil and gas, we are trending to the bottom end of the range of $1.60 to $1.70 EPS for the year,"
Immelt said.
  The FactSet consensus for 2017 adjusted EPS is $1.62.
  Analyst Jim Corridore at CFRA, which acquired S&P Global's equity and fund-research business last year, followed by
downgrading GE to hold from buy, and by cutting his stock price target to $27 from $36. "With oil and gas weakness
overshadowing strength in aerospace and health, we now think there are better investment choices with likely higher EPS
growth prospects in the industrial sector," Corridore wrote in a note to clients.
  Some investors seem to believe GE's fortunes may improve after incoming CEO John Flannery takes over on Aug. 1. When
the CEO change was announced on June 12, the stock surged 3.6%. Since the announcement, however, the stock has plunged
10.5% to close Friday at the lowest price since Oct. 2, 2015.
  Don't miss: General Electric (GE) CEO Immelt will step down after 16 years at the company (http://www.marketwatch.com/
story/general-electric-ceo-immelt-will-step-down-after-16-years-at-company-2017-06-12).
  As MarketWatch previously reported (http://www.marketwatch.com/story/ges-stock-is-the-worst-dow-performer-since-
immelt-took-charge-2017-06-12), the stock has been the Dow's worst-performing component during the 16 years Immelt has
been in charge. The year-to-date decline of 18.0% makes it the weakest Dow stock this year.
  If there is a silver lining for investors, GE's stock is currently the lowest priced within the Dow, which means it
has the least influence. The 78-cent, or 2.9% drop shaved just 5 points off the price of the Dow, which lost 32 points.
See Market Snapshot (http://www.marketwatch.com/story/nasdaq-win-streak-in-doubt-as-stock-futures-limp-ahead-of-ge-
honeywell-2017-07-21).
  By comparison, Goldman Sachs Group Inc.'s stock fell just 1.0%, but the $2.12 price drop took over 14 points off the
Dow.
  Immelt ended Friday's conference call by thanking the GE finance team, and by saying he just wanted investors to
appreciate the "incredible work" that has gone into the 64 quarterly reports that have been released since he was in
charge.
  "So, again, I'm sure I'll see many of you investors over time, but I want to use this as an opportunity to do a shout
out for the GE team and what great work they do," Immelt said.
  -Tomi Kilgore; 415-439-6400; AskNewswires@dowjones.com



  (END) Dow Jones Newswires
  07-22-17 1003ET
